<font color="#FF0000">THE SOUL OF THE PROTESTOR</font><br>
<tt>Wed May 14 17:59:04 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Ok, I have been asked to explain what it FELT like to be a protestor.  This is difficult. Difficult in the light of hindsight and reality, so please bare with me. PART ONE:<br><br>
A very brief bio is in order to set the stage. I was born in a solid blue collar (I was the first to graduate college) family, and my Dad was a Tool &amp; Die Maker, (high end machinist) and active unionist (he was always organizing to get better wages, etc., and it seems the union always lost at the election, the &quot;bosses&quot; gave out raises, etc., and the union broke his heart, but not his spirit). I get some of my tenacity from him. Civil Rights, the A.C.L.U. and the Democratic Party were the family's religion. Mom was a full time at home mom, and dad worked 6+ days a week.  Critical thinking and challenging authority was the norm, and my parents had many a conference with Vice Principals over the years, about my &quot;non conformity&quot;. I grew up in a neighborhood of $8,000 homes (1953 price) where every other father worked for Douglass Aircraft -Long Beach, or the Long Beach Navy Yard.<br><br>
My senior year in H.S. found me in an honors class, and involved in global ideas, philosophy, and civil rights activism. I was a idealized white kid helping Black's in the Ghetto sign up to vote.  Met Martin Luther King one night and sang We Shall Overcome with him.  Shook hands at a Democratic Rally with JFK that summer. Man I was too cool.<br><br>
Civil Rights gradually let to anti-war thinking as a world wide, universal type of thinking. I registered for the draft at 18 (on my birthday-and felt proud) (1963). Then I began to read and listen, and learn about Viet Nam, The Bay of Tonkin, and what I was not being told, in between the lines. My civil rights activitism became anti-war actitism, and I became a &quot;draft counselor&quot; at the local peace center/free clinic.  Then my world got turned all around.<br><br>
I got my first &quot;classification&quot; and the draft now became all too real. I knew if I dropped out of college I was nam bound. Stir in drugs and presto-chango, a radical was born.  My hair grew longer, my politics more extreme.  As bizarre as this sounds now, I felt I was in a war every day of my life, againist &quot;the establishment&quot; and &quot;the system&quot; and I was a modern day outlaw-resistor.  God this does not stand the test of time. I feel (right now) like a damn fool writing this but this is how I felt then.  Time Magazine coined the word &quot;hippy&quot;, I always hated it.  We were radicals, outlaws, freaks, but not hippy's.<br><br>
How does a lifestyle feel?  I lived in an old house with several others. Had an &quot;old lady&quot; and long hair, went to college and got A's and B's in Political Science, smoked dope, dropped acid, and felt we/I were the vanguard of change for the country.  Life was sex,drugs, rock &amp; roll, and that damn draft card in my wallet. Always there to remind me that the jungle was just one mistake away, that prison was just one mistake away.  I think this subtle pressure directly related to the spread of drugs and drug taking, fostering a devil-may-care-attitude among almost everyone I knew.<br><br>
I felt my &quot;mission&quot; was to teach, to radicalize, to draft counsel others out of going into the service.  There were protestors who just did there thing at monthly demonstrations, others in between, and a few like me, that were the hard core, the Students for a Democratic Society (SDS), and everyday was a day of battle.  (God, how this sounds now, after all the jungle and pain stories I have heard and seen -the movies- over the years). <br><br>
The real battle I fought was with Local Draft Board #125. That was the personalization of the war.  5 community members who held my life in their conservative opinion. They were my enemy.  When Student Deferments ment that you automatically became 1-A upon graduation, I refused my II-S. I was immediately classified 1'A.  I went to my first Armed Forces Induction Physical with my heart in my mouth, and peace emblems drawn all over my boxer shorts.  I got roughed up by some military types, hit in the face with a stapler, and kicked out with my clothing in my hand. I knew that the military were all nazi's and I was the good guy.<br><br>
2 months latter another physical, and I got a few stiches too boot.  I was paranoid. I felt the FBI was following me, or at least the CIA, if not the local Narks. Hindsight: obviously the drugs and ol Tim Leary contributed a bit.<br><br>
Everyday was a day filled with extremes, of feelings, of emotions, of seeing the daily body count on the T.V. and planning what &quot;we&quot; could do to wake up the country and end this murder-war.  My parents said go to Canada.  That wasn't right for me.  I wandered around Europe, fell in with some Israeli's on their way home (a call up), and ended up working on a Kibbutz when the 6 day war happened.  I toured the battlefields within days, saw melted tanks, a desert filled with shoes, body parts, and death.  I also saw a county victorious in a &quot;just&quot; war.  I felt more than ever that the &quot;unjust&quot; war of Viet Nam was wrong, and had to be stopped.  Something clicked in me, and I returned to face and fight it out with Local Board #125.<br><br>
2 years later I was given (after many lawyers, the ACLU, others) a C.O.Status because my &quot;political thinking occupied a place in my mind equal to that of a religion&quot;. In otherwords, I was the first to get a C.O. for Non-Religious grounds (i.e. The Quakers, Friends, etc. were automatic C.O.'s).  I felt a personal victory because I felt, in my small way, I had changed the system, and oppened a door for others. 6 months later I started working graveyard as a ward clerk in a county hospital.<br><br>
2 years later, (and friends, excuse me for this one) I felt like a vet.  I had done my own tour of duty (Yes, I know NOW how it pales in comparison to many of yours), but I was safe, had done my duty to my country legally, and could hold my head up.  I also applied for G.I.Bill to go back to college, and was told I had no Veteran rights or benefits.  I felt that was wrong, and also began to fight on behalf of other C.O.'s for &quot;earned&quot; rights. I truly believed that I was entitled to some form of benefits, even if a token amount compared to battleground vets. I was not a destroyer, just in exile within my country. Yes I wanted recognition (and I guess I still do - and have gotten that here on this site thanks to many of you).. At the time, I got nothing. McNamara's book gave me a taste that I was right. This site has given me a banquet, and I thank you all.  <br><br>
Man, (and ladies), did I answer the question?  I'll be back with Part Two in case I didn't.  This is hard, after 30 years, to go back and get inside my own head as a young man in his early 20's.  Anyone know a good shrink?<br><br>
Doc Spatz<br>
 
